--- title: "Take Home Exercise 2" author: "Nor Hendra" date: "22 May 2025" date-modified: "last-modified" format: html editor: visual freeze: true execute: eval: true echo: true warning: false code-fold: true --- ```{=html} ``` # Mini-Challenge 1: Question 2 For Take-home Exercise 2, my group members ([Andre](https://isss608-ay2025-aprilterm.netlify.app/), [Jin Yao](https://isss608-blessmebellburve.netlify.app/)) and I have decided to do [Mini-Challenge 1](https://vast-challenge.github.io/2025/MC1.html). Through our discussion (and the help of a wheel randomizer), we split the challenge's questions amongst ourselves. Jin Yao will be doing question 1, myself will be doing question 2 and Andre will be doing question 3. **Question 2:** Develop visualizations that illustrate how the influence of Oceanus Folk has spread through the musical world. 1. Was this influence intermittent or did it have a gradual rise? 2. What genres and top artists have been most influenced by Oceanus Folk? 3. On the converse, how has Oceanus Folk changed with the rise of Sailor Shift? From which genres does it draw most of its contemporary inspiration? ## 1.1 Installing Packages In the code chunk below, p_load() of pacman package is used to load the R packages into R environment ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} pacman::p_load(tidyverse,jsonlite,SmartEDA,tidygraph,ggraph,gganimate, scales, ggplot2, gifski, plotly,dplyr, knitr, visNetwork,igraph) ``` ::: ## 1.2 Importing Knowledge Graph Data In the code chunk below, `fromJSON()` of **jsonlite** package is used to import *MC1_graph.json* file into R and save the output object. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} kg <- fromJSON("data/MC1_graph.json") ``` ::: ### Inspect structure ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} str(kg, max.level =1) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` List of 5 $ directed : logi TRUE $ multigraph: logi TRUE $ graph :List of 2 $ nodes :'data.frame': 17412 obs. of 10 variables: $ links :'data.frame': 37857 obs. of 4 variables: ``` ::: ::: ### Extract and inspect ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} nodes_tbl <- as_tibble(kg$nodes) links_tbl <- as_tibble(kg$links) ``` ::: # 2. Data Preparation ### Step 1: Build a clean nodes table ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} nodes_clean <- nodes_tbl %>% mutate( date_raw = coalesce(release_date, written_date, notoriety_date), date_parsed = parse_date_time(date_raw, orders = c("Ymd","Y-m-d","Y"), quiet = TRUE), year = year(date_parsed), rowid = row_number() ) %>% select(rowid, id, name, `Node Type`, genre, year) ``` ::: This ensures each id from node list is mapped to the correct row number ### Step 2: Build a clean edges table ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} edges_clean <- links_tbl %>% rename(source_id = source, target_id = target) %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(id, rowid), by = c("source_id" = "id")) %>% rename(from = rowid) %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(id, rowid), by = c("target_id" = "id")) %>% rename(to = rowid) %>% filter(!is.na(from) & !is.na(to)) ``` ::: ## 2.1 Data Preparation - for Question 2A ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} infl_edges <- edges_clean %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, source_genre = genre), by = c("from" = "rowid")) %>% filter(source_genre == "Oceanus Folk") %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, target_year = year), by = c("to" = "rowid")) %>% filter(!is.na(target_year)) #Summarise and compute the cumulative count over time yearly <- infl_edges %>% count(target_year, name = "new_influences") %>% arrange(target_year) %>% mutate(cumulative = cumsum(new_influences)) ``` ::: # Mini-Challenge 1: Question 2 # Sailing the Sound: Oceanus Folk’s Global Journey ```{=html} ``` Sailor Shift is one of the defining musical icons of her generation, a global superstar whose journey began on the quiet, coastal island nation of Oceanus. Rooted in the soul-stirring genre of Oceanus Folk, Sailor’s early music echoed the traditions of her homeland, capturing the attention of local audiences with its authenticity and emotional depth. Her rise began in earnest in 2023 as the lead vocalist of Ivy Echoes, an all-female band that helped bring Oceanus Folk into the contemporary spotlight. Though the band disbanded by 2026, Sailor’s solo breakthrough came just two years later when a viral single catapulted her into global recognition which marked the first time an Oceanus Folk track topped the international charts. Since then, Sailor has released a new album almost every year, each more successful than the last. While she has evolved musically, often blending elements of Indie Pop and Indie Folk, she remains a proud champion of Oceanus Folk. Her collaborations with both rising and established artists have not only expanded her reach but also served to amplify the genre itself. Sailor’s enduring commitment to uplifting lesser-known musicians and promoting the music of her roots has helped fuel a cultural resurgence, drawing global attention to Oceanus and inspiring a new wave of artists from the region. Now, in 2040, as she returns home, Sailor Shift is more than just a musician - she is a movement. Her story, and that of the Oceanus Folk genre she helped elevate, is the subject of a new investigation by local journalist Silas Reed. By visualizing a detailed knowledge graph of her career, collaborations, and influence, we uncover not just the legacy of one artist, but the rise of a cultural phenomenon. ## Question 2 (Part A) ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} milestones <- tibble( milestone_year = 2028, label = "2028: Sailor’s Breakthrough" ) %>% left_join(yearly, by = c("milestone_year" = "target_year")) p_anim <- ggplot(yearly, aes(x = target_year)) + geom_col(aes(y = new_influences, fill = "Annual New Influences"), alpha = 0.8, show.legend = TRUE) + geom_line(aes(y = cumulative, color = "Cumulative Releases"), size = 1.2, show.legend = TRUE) + geom_point(aes(y = cumulative, color = "Cumulative Releases"), size = 2) + geom_segment(data = milestones, aes(x = milestone_year, xend = milestone_year, y = 0, yend = cumulative), arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.2, "cm")), color = "firebrick", size = 0.5) + geom_text(data = milestones, aes(x = milestone_year, y = cumulative, label = label), vjust = -0.2, hjust = 0.5, color = "firebrick", size = 5) + scale_fill_manual(name = NULL, values = c("Annual New Influences" = "blue")) + scale_color_manual(name = NULL, values = c("Cumulative Releases" = "black")) + guides( fill = guide_legend(nrow = 1, byrow = TRUE, override.aes = list(color = NA)), color = guide_legend(nrow = 1, byrow = TRUE, override.aes = list(linetype = 1, shape = 16, size = 2, fill = NA)) ) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = pretty_breaks(10), minor_breaks = seq(min(yearly$target_year),2040,by = 1), expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.05))) + scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,400), expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0))) + coord_cartesian(clip = "off") + labs( title = "Global Oceanus Folk Influence", x = "Year", y = "Cumulative Releases" ) + theme_minimal(base_size = 14) + theme( panel.grid = element_blank(), plot.title.position = "plot", plot.title = element_text(hjust=0.5, size=18, face="bold"), axis.line = element_line(color = "black"), axis.ticks.length = unit(3, "pt"), legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "horizontal", legend.key = element_rect(fill = NA, color = NA), plot.margin = margin(t = 20, r = 40, b = 10, l = 10), panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey80", size = 0.2), panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "grey90", size = 0.2), panel.clip = "off" ) + transition_reveal(target_year) + ease_aes("linear") animate( p_anim, nframes = length(unique(yearly$target_year)), fps = 5, renderer = gifski_renderer("oceanus_folk_final.gif") ) p_anim ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](Take-home_Ex02-copy_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.gif) ::: ::: Between 1980 and 1995, the influence curve is essentially flat where new outside releases are virtually nonexistent, and the cumulative total barely budges. Beginning in the late 1990s, you can spot the very first trickles of interest, but it isn’t until around 2003 that the genre truly starts climbing, with a steadily steeper rise that continues through 2009. At that point, a pronounced burst of annual “new influences” propels the cumulative count sharply upward. After a brief lull, a second, even more dramatic surge takes hold from 2009 onward, driving the line into a rapid ascent. These distinct phases of long early inactivity, a gradual pick-up, and two major waves make it clear that Oceanus Folk’s global spread happened in intermittent pulses rather than as a smooth, continuous progression. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} plot_ly( data = yearly, x = ~target_year, y = ~new_influences, type = "bar", name = "Annual New Influences", marker = list(color = "blue"), hoverinfo = "text", hovertext = ~paste0( "Year: ", target_year, "
New Influences: ", new_influences ) ) %>% add_trace( y = ~cumulative, type = "scatter", mode = "lines+markers", name = "Cumulative Releases", line = list(color = "black", width = 2), marker = list(color = "firebrick", size = 6), hoverinfo = "text", hovertext = ~paste0( "Year: ", target_year, "
Cumulative: ", cumulative ) ) %>% layout( title = list( text = "Global Oceanus Folk Influence", y = 0.95, font = list( size = 24, family = "Arial" ) ), xaxis = list( title = list(text = "Year", standoff = 4), tickmode = "linear", dtick = 5, automargin = TRUE ), yaxis = list( title = "Cumulative Releases", range = c(0, 400), tickmode = "linear", dtick = 100, showgrid = TRUE, gridcolor = "lightgray", gridwidth = 1 ), legend = list( orientation = "h", xanchor = "center", x = 0.5, y = -0.08, yanchor = "top" ), margin = list( t = 80, # <— plenty of room for the title now b = 30 ), shapes = list( list( type = "line", xref = "paper", x0 = 0, x1 = 1, yref = "y", y0 = 400, y1 = 400, line = list(color = "lightgray", width = 2) ) ) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: Based on the interactive plot above, we can see that 2010 had the most new releases totalling 96 of the Oceanus Folk genre which eventually led to the steep increase in the genre's popularity. We know Sailor Shift did not come into the picture until her breakthrough in 2028 so who exactly drove this growth of Oceanus Folk? ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # 1. Compute top_drivers as before top_drivers <- edges_clean %>% left_join( nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, source_genre = genre), by = c("from" = "rowid") ) %>% filter(source_genre == "Oceanus Folk") %>% left_join( nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, target_year = year), by = c("to" = "rowid") ) %>% filter(!is.na(target_year), target_year == 2010) %>% left_join( nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, name, node_type = `Node Type`), by = c("from" = "rowid") ) %>% count(name, node_type, sort = TRUE, name = "n_links") %>% slice_head(n = 96) # 2. Render as a simple HTML table library(DT) datatable( top_drivers, colnames = c("Artist", "Type", "Number of Links"), caption = "Contributing Artists to Oceanus Folk Sources Driving the Surge in 2010", options = list(pageLength = 10, autoWidth = TRUE) ) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: All 96 artists released a song or an album to drive the surge from 2010 onward. We do see a steep increase, but who are the top contributors for this genre post-2010 surge? ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # Top 10 contributors from 2010 onward top_10_contributors <- edges_clean %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, source_genre = genre), by = c("from" = "rowid")) %>% filter(source_genre == "Oceanus Folk") %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, target_year = year), by = c("to" = "rowid")) %>% filter(!is.na(target_year), target_year >= 2010) %>% left_join(nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, name, node_type = `Node Type`), by = c("from" = "rowid")) %>% count(name, node_type, sort = TRUE, name = "n_links") %>% slice_head(n = 10) max_links <- max(top_10_contributors$n_links) integer_breaks <- seq(0, max_links, by = 1) ggplot(top_10_contributors, aes(x = reorder(name, n_links), y = n_links, fill = node_type)) + geom_col(width = 0.7) + coord_flip() + scale_y_continuous( breaks = integer_breaks, expand = expansion(mult = c(0, 0.05)) ) + scale_fill_brewer( type = "qual", palette = "Set2", name = "Release Type" ) + labs( title = "Top 10 Oceanus Folk Artists Driving the Post-2010 Surge", x = "Artist", y = "Number of Releases" ) + theme_minimal(base_size = 14) + theme( panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), axis.line.x = element_line(color = "black"), axis.line.y = element_line(color = "black"), plot.title = element_text(color = "black", face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5), axis.title.x = element_text(color = "black", size = 16, face="bold"), axis.title.y = element_text(color = "black", size = 16, face="bold"), axis.text = element_text(size =12, color = "black"), legend.title = element_text(color = "black"), legend.text = element_text(color = "black"), legend.position = "bottom" ) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](Take-home_Ex02-copy_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-11-1.png){width=960} ::: ::: We can see Palm of Passage released the most songs with 7 releases from 2010 onwards. These top 10 artists are key drivers that contributed to Oceanus Folk genre' surge to a steep increase. # Question 2 (Part B) ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # 1. First‐degree: Oceanus Folk → target genres first_deg <- infl_edges %>% left_join( nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, target_genre = genre), by = c("to" = "rowid") ) %>% filter(!is.na(target_genre)) %>% transmute(from = "Oceanus Folk", to = target_genre) # 2. genre→genre edges from edges_clean genre2genre <- edges_clean %>% left_join( nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, source_genre = genre), by = c("from" = "rowid") ) %>% left_join( nodes_clean %>% select(rowid, target_genre = genre), by = c("to" = "rowid") ) %>% filter(!is.na(source_genre) & !is.na(target_genre)) %>% transmute(from = source_genre, to = target_genre) # 3. Combine and BFS to depth 4 all_edges <- bind_rows(first_deg, genre2genre) g <- graph_from_data_frame(all_edges, directed = TRUE) bfs_res <- bfs(g, root = "Oceanus Folk", neimode = "out", dist = TRUE) valid_genres <- V(g)$name[!is.na(bfs_res$dist) & bfs_res$dist <= 4] sub_edges <- all_edges %>% filter(from %in% valid_genres & to %in% valid_genres) # 4. Build nodes frame nodes_vis <- tibble( id = valid_genres, label = valid_genres, group = case_when( id == "Oceanus Folk" ~ "Source", id %in% first_deg$to ~ "Direct", TRUE ~ "Tertiary+" ) ) # 5. Build edges frame (dummy value=1 for thickness) edges_vis <- sub_edges %>% mutate(value = 1) # 6. Render with repulsion visNetwork(nodes_vis, edges_vis, height = "600px", width = "100%") %>% visNodes(shape = "dot") %>% visEdges(arrows = "to", color = list(color = "gray80")) %>% visOptions(highlightNearest = list(enabled = TRUE, degree = 1), nodesIdSelection = TRUE) %>% visLegend() %>% visPhysics(solver = "repulsion", repulsion = list(nodeDistance = 200, centralGravity = 0.3)) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: :::
